The number of homes sold in the UK is expected to fall by 60% in the next three months, according to the property website Zoopla. There was a 40% drop in housing enquiries for the week to 22 March, the week before the nationwide lockdown, and new sales agreed fell by 15% on the previous week. The trend is expected to worsen considerably in the coming months. The need for physical distancing and government advice to stay at home mean buyers and renters are unable to view properties in person. Some estate agents have switched to virtual viewings. The housing minister, Robert Jenrick, said on Twitter: â€œBuyers and renters should, as far as possible, delay moving to a new house while emergency measures are in place. If moving is unavoidable because youâ€™re contracted and the parties arenâ€™t able to agree a delay, you must follow advice on social distancing when moving.â€ Many people have asked, what to do if youâ€™re moving house at this time?@mhclg has worked with @TheLawSociety to ensure people are properly advised.ğŸ”¹Buyers & renters should, as far as possible, delay moving to a new house while emergency measures are in place. 1/2 Vicky Bibiris, the managing director of Location Location, a north London estate agents, said so far only one sale had fallen through because of a job loss, out of 40 transactions in the agencyâ€™s pipeline. She said that after the EU referendum the number of sales plunged immediately, whereas this time the impact was more gradual. She estimated Location Location could face a 20% drop in transactions in the next few months. Separate research from the upmarket estate agents Savills said that if a sharp drop in demand was extended until September, total transactions for 2020 would be between 566,000 and 745,000, compared with the 1.027m forecast last November. â€œSuppressed demand would be expected to return relatively quickly to the market and we could see a return to normal levels by May 2021â€, it said. Noble Francis, an honorary profe